cais)]] a lighthouse on the outskirts of the Portuguese town of Cascais\n* [[Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria]], commonly known as Gu\u00eda, a municipality on Grand Canary island, Canary Islands\n* [[Flor de Gu\u00eda cheese]], a cheese made in the Canary Islands\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "name_user": "Error", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:*Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de Gu\u00eda, a Catholic image in the Philippines.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guia"}
{"title_page": "Cobalt-60", "text_new": "{{short description|Radioactive isotope of cobalt}}\n{{about|the [[nuclide]] cobalt-60}}\n{{Infobox isotope\n|num_neutrons = 33\n|num_protons = 27\n|alternate_names = \n|mass_number=60\n|abundance = [[trace radioisotope|trace]]\n|symbol=Co\n|decay_product = {{SimpleNuclide2|nickel|60}}\n|halflife= 5.27 years<ref>\n{{cite web\n |title=Radionuclide Half-Life Measurements \n |url=https://www.nist.gov/pml/data/halflife-html.cfm \n |author=National Institute of Standards and Technology\n |accessdate=2011-11-07\n}}</ref>\n|mass=59.9338222\n|excess_energy =\n|error1 =\n|binding_energy =\n|error2 =\n|spin =5+\n|decay_mode1= \u03b2 ([[beta decay]])\n|decay_mode2 = \u03b3 ([[gamma-rays]])\n|decay_energy1= 0.317<ref>\n{{cite web\n |title=Chart of Nucleids \n |url=https://www.nndc.bnl.gov/chart/\n |author=National Nuclear Data Center, Brookhaven\n |accessdate=2018-10-25\n}}</ref>\n|decay_energy2 =1.1732,1.3325\n}}\n[[File:60Co gamma spectrum energy.png|thumb|right|&gamma;-ray spectrum of cobalt-60]]\n\n'''Cobalt-60''' (<sup>60</sup>Co), is a [[synthetic isotope|synthetic]] [[radioactive]] [[Isotopes of cobalt|isotope of cobalt]] with a [[half-life]] of 5.2713 years.<ref name=ICRP107>{{cite journal |title=Nuclear Decay Data for Dosimetric Calculations |journal=Annals of the ICRP |year=2008 |volume=38 |series=ICRP Publication 107 |issue=3 |url=http://www.icrp.org/publication.asp?id=ICRP%20Publication%20107 }}</ref> It is produced artificially in [[nuclear reactor]]s. Deliberate industrial production depends on [[neutron activation]] of bulk samples of the [[Monoisotopic element|monoisotopic]] and [[Mononuclidic element|mononuclidic]] [[cobalt]] [[isotope]] {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|59|link=yes}}.<ref>Malkoske, G. R. [http://www.nuclearfaq.ca/malkoskie_cobalt_paper.pdf ''Cobalt-60 production in CANDU power reactors'']</ref> Measurable quantities are also produced as a by-product of typical nuclear power plant operation and may be detected externally when leaks occur. In the latter case (in the absence of added cobalt) the incidentally produced {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} is largely the result of multiple stages of neutron activation of [[Isotopes of iron|iron isotopes]] in the reactor's steel structures<ref>US [[Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] [http://www.epa.gov/radiation/radionuclides/cobalt.html#wheredoes Radiation Protection: Cobalt]</ref> via the creation of its {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|59}} precursor. The simplest case of the latter would result from the activation of {{SimpleNuclide2|iron|58|link=yes}}. {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} decays by [[beta decay]] to the stable isotope [[nickel-60]] ({{SimpleNuclide2|nickel|60}}). The activated nickel nucleus emits two [[gamma ray]]s with energies of 1.17 and 1.33 [[megaelectronvolt|MeV]], hence the overall nuclear equation of the reaction is {{nuclide|cobalt|59}} + n \u2192 {{nuclide|cobalt|60}} \u2192 {{nuclide|nickel|60}} + e<sup>\u2212</sup> + {{SubatomicParticle|Electron antineutrino}} + gamma rays.\n\n==Activity==\nCorresponding to its half-life the [[Radioactive decay#Radioactive decay rates|radioactive activity]] of one [[gram]] of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} is 44 [[tera-|T]][[becquerel|Bq]] (about 1100 [[curie]]s). The ''absorbed dose constant'' is related to the decay energy and time. For {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} it is equal to 0.35 mSv/(GBq h) at one meter from the source. This allows calculation of the [[equivalent dose]], which depends on distance and activity.\n\nExample: a {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} source with an activity of 2.8 GBq, which is equivalent to 60&nbsp;\u00b5g of pure {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}}, generates a dose of 1 mSv at one meter distance within one hour. The swallowing of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} reduces the distance to a few millimeters, and the same dose is achieved within seconds.\n\nTest sources, such as those used for school experiments, have an activity of <100 kBq. Devices for nondestructive material testing use sources with activities of 1 TBq and more.\n\nThe high \u03b3-energies result in a significant mass difference between {{SimpleNuclide2|nickel|60}} and {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} of 0.003 [[atomic mass unit|u]]. This amounts to nearly 20 watts per gram, nearly 30 times larger than that of {{SimpleNuclide2|plutonium|238}}.\n\n==Decay==\n[[File:Cobalt-60m-decay.svg|thumb|The [[decay scheme]] of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} and {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60m}}.]]\nThe diagram shows a (simplified) [[decay scheme]] of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} and {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60m}}. The main \u03b2-decay transitions are shown. The probability for population of the middle energy level of 2.1&nbsp;MeV by \u03b2-decay is 0.0022%, with a maximum energy of 665.26&nbsp;keV. Energy transfers between the three levels generate six different gamma-ray frequencies.<ref name=\"LUNuclearData\">{{cite web |url=http://nucleardata.nuclear.lu.se/toi/nuclide.asp?iZA=270060 |title=Table of Isotopes decay data |accessdate=April 16, 2012}}</ref> In the diagram the two important ones are marked. [[Internal conversion]] energies are well below the main energy levels.\n\n{{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60m}} is a [[nuclear isomer]] of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} with a half-life of 10.467 minutes.<ref name=ICRP107 /> It decays by internal transition to {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}}, emitting 58.6&nbsp;keV gamma rays, or with a low probability (0.22%) by \u03b2-decay into {{SimpleNuclide2|nickel|60}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nucleardata.nuclear.lu.se/toi/nuclide.asp?iZA=270360 |title=Table of Isotopes decay data |accessdate=April 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Applications==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| header   =\n| image1   = CBP X-ray vehicle Superbowl.jpg\n| caption1 = Security screening of cars at the Super Bowl using {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} gamma-ray scanner\n| width1   = 315\n| image2   = Cobalt-60 Irradiator.tif\n| caption2 = Prototype irradiator for [[food irradiation]] to prevent spoilage, 1984. The {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} is in the central pipes\n| width2   = 153\n| footer   =\n}}\n\nThe main advantage of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} is that it is a high intensity gamma-ray emitter with a relatively long half-life, 5.27 years, compared to other gamma ray sources of similar intensity.  The \u03b2-decay energy is low and easily shielded; however, the gamma-ray emission lines have energies around 1.3 MeV, and are highly penetrating.\nThe main uses for {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} are:\n* As a tracer for cobalt in chemical reactions\n* [[Sterilization (microbiology)|Sterilization]] of medical equipment.<ref name=\"IAEAIrradiatorBrochure\">{{cite book |title=Gamma Irradiators For Radiation Processing |publisher=[[International Atomic Energy Agency|IAEA]] |year=2005 |url=http://www-naweb.iaea.org/napc/iachem/Brochgammairradd.pdf}}</ref>\n* Radiation source for medical [[radiotherapy]].<ref name=\"EPAFactSheet\">{{cite web |url=http://www.epa.gov/rpdweb00/radionuclides/cobalt.html |title=Cobalt &#124; Radiation Protection &#124; US EPA |publisher=[[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] |accessdate=April 16, 2012}}</ref>  [[Cobalt therapy]], using beams of gamma rays from {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} [[teletherapy]] machines to treat cancer. \n* Radiation source for [[industrial radiography]].<ref name=\"EPAFactSheet\" />\n* Radiation source for leveling devices and thickness gauges.<ref name=\"EPAFactSheet\" />\n* Radiation source for [[Sterile insect technique|pest insect sterilization]].<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/10/02/us-croatia-farming-nuclear-idUSBRE8910M020121002 Croatia fruit farmers fight flies]</ref>\n* As a radiation source for [[food irradiation]] and [[Blood bank|blood irradiation]].<ref name=\"IAEAIrradiatorBrochure\" />\n\nCobalt has been discussed as a \"[[Salted bomb|salting]]\" element to add to [[nuclear weapon]]s, to produce a [[cobalt bomb]], an extremely \"dirty\" weapon which would contaminate large areas with   {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} [[nuclear fallout]], rendering them uninhabitable.   In one hypothetical design, the  [[neutron reflector|tamper]] of the weapon would be made of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|59}}.  When the bomb exploded, the excess neutrons from the [[nuclear fission]] would irradiate the cobalt and transmute it into {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}}.  No nation is known to have done any serious development of this type of weapon.\n{{multiple image\n| align = center\n| direction = horizontal\n| header   =\n| image1   = HD.17.054 (11951415736).jpg\n| caption1 = {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} needle implanted in tumors for radiotherapy, around 1955. \n| width1   = 135\n| image2   = Nci-vol-1819-300 cobalt 60 therapy.jpg\n| caption2 = {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} [[teletherapy]] machine for cancer radiotherapy, early 1950s.\n| width2   = 264\n| image3   = HD.16.084 (12523991564).jpg\n| caption3 = Brookhaven plant mutation experiment using {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} source in the pipe, center.\n| width3   = 216\n| image4   = Cobalt0001.jpg\n| caption4 = {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} source for sterilizing [[Cochliomyia|screwflies]] in the 1959 Screwworm Eradication Program.\n| width4   = 144\n| footer   =\n}}\n\n==Occurrence==\nThere is no natural {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} in existence on earth; thus, synthetic {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} is created by bombarding a {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|59}} target with a [[thermal neutron|slow neutron]] source. [[Californium-252]], [[neutron moderator|moderated]] through water, can be used for this purpose, as can the neutron flux in a [[nuclear reactor]]. The [[CANDU]] reactors can be used to activate {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|59}}, by substituting the stainless steel control rods with cobalt rods.<ref>[http://www.atomicinsights.com/jun96/isotope.html Isotope Production: Dual Use Power Plants]</ref> In the United States, it is now being produced in a [[BWR]] at [[Hope Creek Nuclear Generating Station]]. The cobalt targets are substituted here for a small number of fuel assemblies.<ref>[http://www.nj.com/salem/index.ssf/2010/11/pseg_nuclears_hope_creek_react_1.html PSEG Nuclear's Hope Creek reactor back on line, begins production of Cobalt-60]</ref>\n:{{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|59}} + n \u2192 {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}}\n\n==Safety==\nAfter entering a living mammal (such as a human being), some of the {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} is excreted in [[feces]]. The remainder is taken up by tissues, mainly the [[liver]], [[kidney]]s, and [[bone]]s, where the prolonged exposure to gamma radiation can cause cancer. Over time, the absorbed cobalt is eliminated in urine.<ref name=\"EPAFactSheet\" />\n\n===Steel contamination===\n\nCobalt is an element used to make [[steel]]. Uncontrolled disposal of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} in scrap metal is responsible for the radioactivity found in several iron-based products.<ref>[https://www.nrc.gov/reading-rm/doc-collections/gen-comm/info-notices/1983/in83016.html radioactive contamination of steel]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaea.org/Publications/Magazines/Bulletin/Bull472/htmls/lessons_learned.html |title=Lessons Learned The Hard Way |work=IAEA Bulletin 47-2 |publisher=International Atomic Energy Agency |accessdate=16 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100718065554/http://www.iaea.org/Publications/Magazines/Bulletin/Bull472/htmls/lessons_learned.html |archivedate=18 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2012, [[Petco]] recalled several models of steel pet food bowls after [[US Customs and Border Protection]] determined that they were emitting low levels of radiation. The source of the radiation was determined to be {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} that had contaminated the steel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://petpitchusa.wordpress.com/2012/08/10/petco-recalls-some-stainless-steel-pet-bowls-due-to-cobalt-60-contamination/|title=Petco Recalls Some Stainless Steel Pet Bowls Due to Cobalt-60 Contamination|accessdate=21 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013 a batch of metal-studded belts sold by online retailer [[ASOS.com|ASOS]] were confiscated and held in a US radioactive storage facility after testing positive for {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sky.com/story/1096486/asos-belts-seized-over-radioactive-studs |title=Asos Belts Seized Over Radioactive Studs |publisher=Sky News |date=2013-05-28 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref>\n\n===Incidents involving medical radiation sources===\n\nIn the [[Samut Prakan radiation accident]] in 2000, a disused radiotherapy head containing a {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} source was stored at an unsecured location in [[Bangkok]], Thailand and then accidentally sold to scrap collectors. Unaware of the dangers, a junkyard employee dismantled the head and extracted the source, which remained unprotected for a period of days at the junkyard. Ten people, including the scrap collectors and workers at the junkyard, were exposed to high levels of radiation and became ill. Three of the junkyard workers subsequently died as a result of their exposure, which was estimated to be over 6&nbsp;[[Gray (unit)|Gy]]. Afterward, the source was safely recovered by the Thai authorities.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Radiological Accident in Samut Prakarn |publisher=[[IAEA]] |year=2002 |url=http://www-pub.iaea.org/MTCD/publications/PDF/Pub1124_scr.pdf |accessdate=2012-04-14}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, a truck carrying a disused 111&nbsp;TBq <sup>60</sup>Co [[teletherapy]] source from a hospital in [[Tijuana]] to a [[radioactive waste]] storage center was hijacked at a gas station near [[Mexico City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rt.com/news/truck-radioactive-stolen-mexico-697 |title=Truck with dangerous radioactive materials hijacked in Mexico - IAEA \u2014 RT News |publisher=RT |date=2013-12-04 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref name=\"IAEAMexico1\">{{cite web |url=http://iaea.org/newscenter/news/2013/mexicoradsource.html |title=Mexico Informs IAEA of Theft of Dangerous Radioactive Source |publisher=IAEA |date= |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref name=\"IAEAMexico2\">{{cite web |url=http://iaea.org/newscenter/news/2013/mexicoradsource2.html |title=Mexico Says Stolen Radioactive Source Found in Field |publisher=IAEA |date=2013-12-05 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref> The truck was recovered shortly after, but it was discovered that the thieves had removed the source from its shielding. It was found abandoned and intact in a field close by.<ref name=\"IAEAMexico2\" /><ref>{{cite web |author=Will Grant |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-25224304 |title=BBC News - Mexico radioactive material found, thieves' lives 'in danger' |publisher=BBC |date=2013-12-05 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref> Despite early reports with lurid headlines asserting that the thieves were \"likely doomed\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20131206/thieves-who-stole-lethal-radioactive-cobalt-60-in-mexico-likely-doomed |title=Thieves who stole lethal radioactive cobalt-60 in Mexico likely doomed |author=Gabriela Martinez, and Joshua Partlow |date= 6 December 2013 |website=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|access-date=12 March 2015}}</ref> the [[radiation sickness]] was mild enough that the suspects were quickly released to police custody,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/other/six-released-mexican-hospital-detained-theft-cobalt-60-f2D11707085 |title=Six released from Mexican hospital but detained in theft of cobalt-60 |author=M. Alex Johnson |date=6 December 2013 |website=[[NBC News]] |access-date=12 March 2015}}</ref> and no one is known to have died from the incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/marycuddehe/what-happens-when-a-truck-carrying-radioactive-material-gets |title=What Happens When A Truck Carrying Radioactive Material Gets Robbed In Mexico |author= Mary Cuddehe |date=13 November 2014 |website=[[BuzzFeed]] |access-date=12 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Parity==\n{{main|Wu experiment}}\nIn 1957, [[Chien-Shiung Wu]] et al.  discovered the \u03b2-decay process violated [[Parity (physics)|parity]], implying nature has a handedness.<ref>\n{{cite journal\n |last1=Wu |first1=C. S.\n |last2=Ambler |first2=E\n |last3=Hayward |first3=R. W.\n |last4=Hoppes |first4=D. D.\n |last5=Hudson |first5=R. P.\n |year=1957\n |title=Experimental Test of Parity Conservation in Beta Decay\n |journal=[[Physical Review]]\n |volume=105 |issue=4 |pages=1413\u20131415\n |bibcode=1957PhRv..105.1413W\n |doi=10.1103/PhysRev.105.1413\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Wu experiment]] her group aligned radioactive {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} nuclei by cooling the source to low temperatures in a magnetic field. Wu's observation was that more \u03b2-rays were emitted in the opposite direction to the nuclear spin.  This asymmetry [[Parity violation|violates]] parity conservation.\n\n==Suppliers==\n\n[[Argentina]], [[Canada]] and [[Russia]] are the largest suppliers of cobalt-60 in the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2017-10-31/the-canadian-ghost-town-that-tesla-is-bringing-back-to-life|title=The Canadian Ghost Town That Tesla Is Bringing Back to Life|date=2017-10-31|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Cobalt bomb]]\n* [[Harold E. Johns]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051130105318/http://www.bt.cdc.gov/radiation/isotopes/cobalt.asp Cobalt-60], Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.\n* [http://toxnet.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-bin/sis/search/r?dbs+hsdb:@term+@na+@rel+cobalt,+radioactive NLM Hazardous Substances Databank&nbsp;\u2013 Cobalt, Radioactive]\n* [http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/nuclear/betaex.html Beta decay of Cobalt-60], HyperPhysics, Georgia State University.\n* {{Cite web|author=Dr. Henry Kelly|url=http://www.fas.org/ssp/docs/030602-kellytestimony.htm|title=Cobalt-60 as a Dirty Bomb|publisher=Federation of American Scientists|date=March 6, 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020405141039/http://www.fas.org/ssp/docs/030602-kellytestimony.htm|archivedate=April 5, 2002|access-date=November 26, 2005|url-status=live}}\n\n{{Isotope|element=cobalt|lighter=[[cobalt-59]]|heavier=[[cobalt-61]]|before=[[iron-60]]|after=[[nickel-60]]}}\n\n[[Category:Isotopes of cobalt]]\n[[Category:Radioactive contamination]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the [[nuclide]] cobalt-60}}\n{{Infobox isotope\n|num_neutrons = 33\n|num_protons = 27\n|alternate_names = \n|mass_number=60\n|abundance = [[trace radioisotope|trace]]\n|symbol=Co\n|decay_product = {{SimpleNuclide2|nickel|60}}\n|halflife= 5.27 years<ref>\n{{cite web\n |title=Radionuclide Half-Life Measurements \n |url=https://www.nist.gov/pml/data/halflife-html.cfm \n |author=National Institute of Standards and Technology\n |accessdate=2011-11-07\n}}</ref>\n|mass=59.9338222\n|excess_energy =\n|error1 =\n|binding_energy =\n|error2 =\n|spin =5+\n|decay_mode1= \u03b2 ([[beta decay]])\n|decay_mode2 = \u03b3 ([[gamma-rays]])\n|decay_energy1= 0.317<ref>\n{{cite web\n |title=Chart of Nucleids \n |url=https://www.nndc.bnl.gov/chart/\n |author=National Nuclear Data Center, Brookhaven\n |accessdate=2018-10-25\n}}</ref>\n|decay_energy2 =1.1732,1.3325\n}}\n[[File:60Co gamma spectrum energy.png|thumb|right|&gamma;-ray spectrum of cobalt-60]]\n\n'''Cobalt-60''' (<sup>60</sup>Co), is a [[synthetic isotope|synthetic]] [[radioactive]] [[Isotopes of cobalt|isotope of cobalt]] with a [[half-life]] of 5.2713 years.<ref name=ICRP107>{{cite journal |title=Nuclear Decay Data for Dosimetric Calculations |journal=Annals of the ICRP |year=2008 |volume=38 |series=ICRP Publication 107 |issue=3 |url=http://www.icrp.org/publication.asp?id=ICRP%20Publication%20107 }}</ref> It is produced artificially in [[nuclear reactor]]s. Deliberate industrial production depends on [[neutron activation]] of bulk samples of the [[Monoisotopic element|monoisotopic]] and [[Mononuclidic element|mononuclidic]] [[cobalt]] [[isotope]] {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|59|link=yes}}.<ref>Malkoske, G. R. [http://www.nuclearfaq.ca/malkoskie_cobalt_paper.pdf ''Cobalt-60 production in CANDU power reactors'']</ref> Measurable quantities are also produced as a by-product of typical nuclear power plant operation and may be detected externally when leaks occur. In the latter case (in the absence of added cobalt) the incidentally produced {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} is largely the result of multiple stages of neutron activation of [[Isotopes of iron|iron isotopes]] in the reactor's steel structures<ref>US [[Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] [http://www.epa.gov/radiation/radionuclides/cobalt.html#wheredoes Radiation Protection: Cobalt]</ref> via the creation of its {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|59}} precursor. The simplest case of the latter would result from the activation of {{SimpleNuclide2|iron|58|link=yes}}. {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} decays by [[beta decay]] to the stable isotope [[nickel-60]] ({{SimpleNuclide2|nickel|60}}). The activated nickel nucleus emits two [[gamma ray]]s with energies of 1.17 and 1.33 [[megaelectronvolt|MeV]], hence the overall nuclear equation of the reaction is {{nuclide|cobalt|59}} + n \u2192 {{nuclide|cobalt|60}} \u2192 {{nuclide|nickel|60}} + e<sup>\u2212</sup> + {{SubatomicParticle|Electron antineutrino}} + gamma rays.\n\n==Activity==\nCorresponding to its half-life the [[Radioactive decay#Radioactive decay rates|radioactive activity]] of one [[gram]] of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} is 44 [[tera-|T]][[becquerel|Bq]] (about 1100 [[curie]]s). The ''absorbed dose constant'' is related to the decay energy and time. For {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} it is equal to 0.35 mSv/(GBq h) at one meter from the source. This allows calculation of the [[equivalent dose]], which depends on distance and activity.\n\nExample: a {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} source with an activity of 2.8 GBq, which is equivalent to 60&nbsp;\u00b5g of pure {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}}, generates a dose of 1 mSv at one meter distance within one hour. The swallowing of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} reduces the distance to a few millimeters, and the same dose is achieved within seconds.\n\nTest sources, such as those used for school experiments, have an activity of <100 kBq. Devices for nondestructive material testing use sources with activities of 1 TBq and more.\n\nThe high \u03b3-energies result in a significant mass difference between {{SimpleNuclide2|nickel|60}} and {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} of 0.003 [[atomic mass unit|u]]. This amounts to nearly 20 watts per gram, nearly 30 times larger than that of {{SimpleNuclide2|plutonium|238}}.\n\n==Decay==\n[[File:Cobalt-60m-decay.svg|thumb|The [[decay scheme]] of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} and {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60m}}.]]\nThe diagram shows a (simplified) [[decay scheme]] of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} and {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60m}}. The main \u03b2-decay transitions are shown. The probability for population of the middle energy level of 2.1&nbsp;MeV by \u03b2-decay is 0.0022%, with a maximum energy of 665.26&nbsp;keV. Energy transfers between the three levels generate six different gamma-ray frequencies.<ref name=\"LUNuclearData\">{{cite web |url=http://nucleardata.nuclear.lu.se/toi/nuclide.asp?iZA=270060 |title=Table of Isotopes decay data |accessdate=April 16, 2012}}</ref> In the diagram the two important ones are marked. [[Internal conversion]] energies are well below the main energy levels.\n\n{{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60m}} is a [[nuclear isomer]] of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} with a half-life of 10.467 minutes.<ref name=ICRP107 /> It decays by internal transition to {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}}, emitting 58.6&nbsp;keV gamma rays, or with a low probability (0.22%) by \u03b2-decay into {{SimpleNuclide2|nickel|60}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nucleardata.nuclear.lu.se/toi/nuclide.asp?iZA=270360 |title=Table of Isotopes decay data |accessdate=April 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Applications==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| header   =\n| image1   = CBP X-ray vehicle Superbowl.jpg\n| caption1 = Security screening of cars at the Super Bowl using {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} gamma-ray scanner\n| width1   = 315\n| image2   = Cobalt-60 Irradiator.tif\n| caption2 = Prototype irradiator for [[food irradiation]] to prevent spoilage, 1984. The {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} is in the central pipes\n| width2   = 153\n| footer   =\n}}\n\nThe main advantage of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} is that it is a high intensity gamma-ray emitter with a relatively long half-life, 5.27 years, compared to other gamma ray sources of similar intensity.  The \u03b2-decay energy is low and easily shielded; however, the gamma-ray emission lines have energies around 1.3 MeV, and are highly penetrating.\nThe main uses for {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} are:\n* As a tracer for cobalt in chemical reactions\n* [[Sterilization (microbiology)|Sterilization]] of medical equipment.<ref name=\"IAEAIrradiatorBrochure\">{{cite book |title=Gamma Irradiators For Radiation Processing |publisher=[[International Atomic Energy Agency|IAEA]] |year=2005 |url=http://www-naweb.iaea.org/napc/iachem/Brochgammairradd.pdf}}</ref>\n* Radiation source for medical [[radiotherapy]].<ref name=\"EPAFactSheet\">{{cite web |url=http://www.epa.gov/rpdweb00/radionuclides/cobalt.html |title=Cobalt &#124; Radiation Protection &#124; US EPA |publisher=[[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] |accessdate=April 16, 2012}}</ref>  [[Cobalt therapy]], using beams of gamma rays from {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} [[teletherapy]] machines to treat cancer. \n* Radiation source for [[industrial radiography]].<ref name=\"EPAFactSheet\" />\n* Radiation source for leveling devices and thickness gauges.<ref name=\"EPAFactSheet\" />\n* Radiation source for [[Sterile insect technique|pest insect sterilization]].<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/10/02/us-croatia-farming-nuclear-idUSBRE8910M020121002 Croatia fruit farmers fight flies]</ref>\n* As a radiation source for [[food irradiation]] and [[Blood bank|blood irradiation]].<ref name=\"IAEAIrradiatorBrochure\" />\n\nCobalt has been discussed as a \"[[Salted bomb|salting]]\" element to add to [[nuclear weapon]]s, to produce a [[cobalt bomb]], an extremely \"dirty\" weapon which would contaminate large areas with   {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} [[nuclear fallout]], rendering them uninhabitable.   In one hypothetical design, the  [[neutron reflector|tamper]] of the weapon would be made of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|59}}.  When the bomb exploded, the excess neutrons from the [[nuclear fission]] would irradiate the cobalt and transmute it into {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}}.  No nation is known to have done any serious development of this type of weapon.\n{{multiple image\n| align = center\n| direction = horizontal\n| header   =\n| image1   = HD.17.054 (11951415736).jpg\n| caption1 = {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} needle implanted in tumors for radiotherapy, around 1955. \n| width1   = 135\n| image2   = Nci-vol-1819-300 cobalt 60 therapy.jpg\n| caption2 = {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} [[teletherapy]] machine for cancer radiotherapy, early 1950s.\n| width2   = 264\n| image3   = HD.16.084 (12523991564).jpg\n| caption3 = Brookhaven plant mutation experiment using {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} source in the pipe, center.\n| width3   = 216\n| image4   = Cobalt0001.jpg\n| caption4 = {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} source for sterilizing [[Cochliomyia|screwflies]] in the 1959 Screwworm Eradication Program.\n| width4   = 144\n| footer   =\n}}\n\n==Occurrence==\nThere is no natural {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} in existence on earth; thus, synthetic {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} is created by bombarding a {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|59}} target with a [[thermal neutron|slow neutron]] source. [[Californium-252]], [[neutron moderator|moderated]] through water, can be used for this purpose, as can the neutron flux in a [[nuclear reactor]]. The [[CANDU]] reactors can be used to activate {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|59}}, by substituting the stainless steel control rods with cobalt rods.<ref>[http://www.atomicinsights.com/jun96/isotope.html Isotope Production: Dual Use Power Plants]</ref> In the United States, it is now being produced in a [[BWR]] at [[Hope Creek Nuclear Generating Station]]. The cobalt targets are substituted here for a small number of fuel assemblies.<ref>[http://www.nj.com/salem/index.ssf/2010/11/pseg_nuclears_hope_creek_react_1.html PSEG Nuclear's Hope Creek reactor back on line, begins production of Cobalt-60]</ref>\n:{{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|59}} + n \u2192 {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}}\n\n==Safety==\nAfter entering a living mammal (such as a human being), some of the {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} is excreted in [[feces]]. The remainder is taken up by tissues, mainly the [[liver]], [[kidney]]s, and [[bone]]s, where the prolonged exposure to gamma radiation can cause cancer. Over time, the absorbed cobalt is eliminated in urine.<ref name=\"EPAFactSheet\" />\n\n===Steel contamination===\n\nCobalt is an element used to make [[steel]]. Uncontrolled disposal of {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} in scrap metal is responsible for the radioactivity found in several iron-based products.<ref>[https://www.nrc.gov/reading-rm/doc-collections/gen-comm/info-notices/1983/in83016.html radioactive contamination of steel]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaea.org/Publications/Magazines/Bulletin/Bull472/htmls/lessons_learned.html |title=Lessons Learned The Hard Way |work=IAEA Bulletin 47-2 |publisher=International Atomic Energy Agency |accessdate=16 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100718065554/http://www.iaea.org/Publications/Magazines/Bulletin/Bull472/htmls/lessons_learned.html |archivedate=18 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2012, [[Petco]] recalled several models of steel pet food bowls after [[US Customs and Border Protection]] determined that they were emitting low levels of radiation. The source of the radiation was determined to be {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} that had contaminated the steel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://petpitchusa.wordpress.com/2012/08/10/petco-recalls-some-stainless-steel-pet-bowls-due-to-cobalt-60-contamination/|title=Petco Recalls Some Stainless Steel Pet Bowls Due to Cobalt-60 Contamination|accessdate=21 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013 a batch of metal-studded belts sold by online retailer [[ASOS.com|ASOS]] were confiscated and held in a US radioactive storage facility after testing positive for {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sky.com/story/1096486/asos-belts-seized-over-radioactive-studs |title=Asos Belts Seized Over Radioactive Studs |publisher=Sky News |date=2013-05-28 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref>\n\n===Incidents involving medical radiation sources===\n\nIn the [[Samut Prakan radiation accident]] in 2000, a disused radiotherapy head containing a {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} source was stored at an unsecured location in [[Bangkok]], Thailand and then accidentally sold to scrap collectors. Unaware of the dangers, a junkyard employee dismantled the head and extracted the source, which remained unprotected for a period of days at the junkyard. Ten people, including the scrap collectors and workers at the junkyard, were exposed to high levels of radiation and became ill. Three of the junkyard workers subsequently died as a result of their exposure, which was estimated to be over 6&nbsp;[[Gray (unit)|Gy]]. Afterward, the source was safely recovered by the Thai authorities.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Radiological Accident in Samut Prakarn |publisher=[[IAEA]] |year=2002 |url=http://www-pub.iaea.org/MTCD/publications/PDF/Pub1124_scr.pdf |accessdate=2012-04-14}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, a truck carrying a disused 111&nbsp;TBq <sup>60</sup>Co [[teletherapy]] source from a hospital in [[Tijuana]] to a [[radioactive waste]] storage center was hijacked at a gas station near [[Mexico City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rt.com/news/truck-radioactive-stolen-mexico-697 |title=Truck with dangerous radioactive materials hijacked in Mexico - IAEA \u2014 RT News |publisher=RT |date=2013-12-04 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref name=\"IAEAMexico1\">{{cite web |url=http://iaea.org/newscenter/news/2013/mexicoradsource.html |title=Mexico Informs IAEA of Theft of Dangerous Radioactive Source |publisher=IAEA |date= |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref name=\"IAEAMexico2\">{{cite web |url=http://iaea.org/newscenter/news/2013/mexicoradsource2.html |title=Mexico Says Stolen Radioactive Source Found in Field |publisher=IAEA |date=2013-12-05 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref> The truck was recovered shortly after, but it was discovered that the thieves had removed the source from its shielding. It was found abandoned and intact in a field close by.<ref name=\"IAEAMexico2\" /><ref>{{cite web |author=Will Grant |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-25224304 |title=BBC News - Mexico radioactive material found, thieves' lives 'in danger' |publisher=BBC |date=2013-12-05 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref> Despite early reports with lurid headlines asserting that the thieves were \"likely doomed\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20131206/thieves-who-stole-lethal-radioactive-cobalt-60-in-mexico-likely-doomed |title=Thieves who stole lethal radioactive cobalt-60 in Mexico likely doomed |author=Gabriela Martinez, and Joshua Partlow |date= 6 December 2013 |website=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|access-date=12 March 2015}}</ref> the [[radiation sickness]] was mild enough that the suspects were quickly released to police custody,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/other/six-released-mexican-hospital-detained-theft-cobalt-60-f2D11707085 |title=Six released from Mexican hospital but detained in theft of cobalt-60 |author=M. Alex Johnson |date=6 December 2013 |website=[[NBC News]] |access-date=12 March 2015}}</ref> and no one is known to have died from the incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/marycuddehe/what-happens-when-a-truck-carrying-radioactive-material-gets |title=What Happens When A Truck Carrying Radioactive Material Gets Robbed In Mexico |author= Mary Cuddehe |date=13 November 2014 |website=[[BuzzFeed]] |access-date=12 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Parity==\n{{main|Wu experiment}}\nIn 1957, [[Chien-Shiung Wu]] et al.  discovered the \u03b2-decay process violated [[Parity (physics)|parity]], implying nature has a handedness.<ref>\n{{cite journal\n |last1=Wu |first1=C. S.\n |last2=Ambler |first2=E\n |last3=Hayward |first3=R. W.\n |last4=Hoppes |first4=D. D.\n |last5=Hudson |first5=R. P.\n |year=1957\n |title=Experimental Test of Parity Conservation in Beta Decay\n |journal=[[Physical Review]]\n |volume=105 |issue=4 |pages=1413\u20131415\n |bibcode=1957PhRv..105.1413W\n |doi=10.1103/PhysRev.105.1413\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Wu experiment]] her group aligned radioactive {{SimpleNuclide2|cobalt|60}} nuclei by cooling the source to low temperatures in a magnetic field. Wu's observation was that more \u03b2-rays were emitted in the opposite direction to the nuclear spin.  This asymmetry [[Parity violation|violates]] parity conservation.\n\n==Suppliers==\n\n[[Argentina]], [[Canada]] and [[Russia]] are the largest suppliers of cobalt-60 in the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2017-10-31/the-canadian-ghost-town-that-tesla-is-bringing-back-to-life|title=The Canadian Ghost Town That Tesla Is Bringing Back to Life|date=2017-10-31|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Cobalt bomb]]\n* [[Harold E. Johns]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051130105318/http://www.bt.cdc.gov/radiation/isotopes/cobalt.asp Cobalt-60], Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.\n* [http://toxnet.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-bin/sis/search/r?dbs+hsdb:@term+@na+@rel+cobalt,+radioactive NLM Hazardous Substances Databank&nbsp;\u2013 Cobalt, Radioactive]\n* [http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/nuclear/betaex.html Beta decay of Cobalt-60], HyperPhysics, Georgia State University.\n* {{Cite web|author=Dr. Henry Kelly|url=http://www.fas.org/ssp/docs/030602-kellytestimony.htm|title=Cobalt-60 as a Dirty Bomb|publisher=Federation of American Scientists|date=March 6, 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020405141039/http://www.fas.org/ssp/docs/030602-kellytestimony.htm|archivedate=April 5, 2002|access-date=November 26, 2005|url-status=live}}\n\n{{Isotope|element=cobalt|lighter=[[cobalt-59]]|heavier=[[cobalt-61]]|before=[[iron-60]]|after=[[nickel-60]]}}\n\n[[Category:Isotopes of cobalt]]\n[[Category:Radioactive contamination]]\n", "name_user": "Tridwoxi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Radioactive isotope of cobalt\", overriding Wikidata description \"isotope of cobalt\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cobalt-60"}
